Lesson prerequisites

As usual, we are working within the R project established during the first lesson; therefore, we use relative paths to files. We also assume that we have some subfolders in the folder related to the project (e.g.Â for data, geodata, metadata, results, temporary files, etc.). Good internet connection is required because we will load geographical data directly to R using various services or functions of specialized packages.

If possible, we are working with the newest versions of R (currently, R version 4.3.3 (2024-02-29 ucrt) â Angel Food Cake from 2024-02-29) and RStudio (currently, RStudio 2023.12.1+402 Ocean Storm from 2024-01-29).

Raster geodata in R

There are two main packages for working with raster geodata in R â terra (Hijmans, 2024) and stars (Pebesma and Bivand, 2023). The package stars is developed by the same authors who develop the sf package. So, the names of the functions are similar. Since working with the package stars is based on arrays and it is somehow difficult for beginners, we exclusively work with the terra package and its functions here. terra is a successor to the package raster which was also accompanied by many functions devoted to retrieving some of the geodata directly from the internet. Currently, terra is accompanied by an extra package for this purpose â geodata (Hijmans et al., 2023). It is important to note that also a package has been developed to work with terra objects (usually the type called SpatRaster) in a tidyverse manner â tidyterra (HernangÃ³mez, 2023)1. In addition, this package provides functions for plotting the raster layers using the ggplot2 approach. It is not necessary to have only one-layer SpatRaster objects, but we may also also multiple-layer SpatRaster objects, which allows multiple variables or time series of the same variable in the same objects. SpatRaster objects are very close to lists, so we can manipulate with them in a similar way (e.g.Â subsetting).

Let us show, how to load raster data from a file on the one hand and how to load them while employing the functions of packages such as geodata or RCzechia (Lacko, 2023) on the other. Since we do not have any files in our project subfolders, we will first load some data using the R functions, save them to the files and, lastly, load the data from files.

Basic raster analyses â aggregation over layers, zonal statistics

Let us perform basic analyses by using the functions from the terra package. We can obtain some zonal statistics as well as aggregations over time.

# retrieve some air temperature data over Czechia
airtemp <- worldclim_country(country = "CZE",
                             var = "tavg",
                             path = "geodata")

# we have more layers now
# study their meaning at https://www.worldclim.org/data/worldclim21.html

# assume we want to find the long-term monthly air temperature over individual administrative regions of Czechia in the 1970-2000 period
# first, we will average over all layers to get annual values in cells (using the app() function)
# then, we will compute the zonal statistics for the regions (using the extract() function)

# when working with bigger data, terra creates temporary files
# we can specify where the tempdir should be using the terraOptions() function
terraOptions(tempdir = "tempdir")

airtemp_annual <- app(airtemp,
                      fun = mean,
                      filename = "geodata/airtemp_annual.tif",
                      overwrite = T)

zonalstats <- extract(x = airtemp_annual,
                      y = kraje(),
                      fun = mean,
                      ID = F)

zonalstats <- kraje() |> 
  st_drop_geometry() |> 
  select(NAZ_CZNUTS3) |> 
  bind_cols(zonalstats) |> 
  as_tibble() |> 
  rename(tavg = mean) |> 
  mutate(tavg = round(tavg, 1),
         tavg = units::set_units(tavg, "Â°C"))

When extracting the zonal statistics, the vector and raster layers should be in the same coordinate reference system. In case transformation needs arise, we choose transforming the vector layer. However, not that there is also the project() function in terra for similar purposes when it comes to raster geodata. New versions of terra transform vector layers automatically if we forget.

Raster cropping and masking

From time to time, it is better to crop and mask the raster layers because the original data are too big. Since masking using the shape of a polygon may take a long time without first cropping the raster, the application of the crop() function usually precedes the application of the mask() function.

# we found that the air temperature layers exceed the territory of Czechia
# this must apply also to our annual layer
# however, for some reasons, we need to limit our analyses only to Czechia
# so let us crop and mask the raster layer according to the borders of Czechia
airtemp_annual_masked1 <- airtemp_annual |> 
  crop(republika()) |> 
  mask(republika())

# note we have also a shorter way of masking raster layers if we use the same polygon for cropping and masking
airtemp_annual_masked2 <- airtemp_annual |> 
  crop(republika(),
       mask = T)

# are the layers the same?
identical(airtemp_annual_masked1, airtemp_annual_masked2)
[1] TRUE
ggplot() +
  geom_spatraster(data = airtemp_annual_masked1) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "YlOrRd",
                       direction = 1,
                       na.value = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = republika(),
          col = "purple",
          linewidth = 1,
          fill = NA)

Aspect and slope of the terrain

Often, we need to know about prevailing aspect and slope in our study area. Creation of the aspect and slope raster layers can be done through the terrain() function. Then, we can compute the mean aspect and slope, e.g.Â over administrative regions of Czechia.

# we take only the czdem2 into account
czaspect <- czdem2 |> 
  terrain(v = "aspect")

czslope <- czdem2 |> 
  terrain(v = "slope")

# since the aspect and splope are angular variables, we need to compute the means accordingly
# one of the packages that computes angular means is the package circular
# we are going to compute the means over the administrative regions of Czechia
# we may base our computation on a new raster geodata with two layers
library(circular)

together <- c(czaspect,
              czslope)

# making use of an anonymous function and the conversion to the circular variables
results <- extract(together,
                   kraje(),
                   fun = \(x) mean(circular(x,
                                            units = "degrees"),
                                   na.rm = T),
                   ID = F) |> 
  mutate(aspect = if_else(aspect < 0, 2 * pi - aspect, aspect)) # we do not want the negative values of aspect

# final modification to obtain the resulting tibble
results <- kraje() |> 
  st_drop_geometry() |> 
  select(NAZ_CZNUTS3) |> 
  bind_cols(results) |> 
  as_tibble()

results

Introduction to functional programming in R

Functional programming is very useful when repeating calculation with some of the changed parameters or arguments. It can be effectively used instead of for loops, and it find applications in so-called tidymodeling where many types of models are compared before the final selection of the most effective model having the data at hand. In tidyverse, functional programming is mostly performed by sing the functions of the purrr package. In such functional programming, mainly the map() function and it variants are mainly employed. The machine potential is probably the best utilized when combining functional programming with so-called parallelization (in current R provided by so-called futures and the furrr package).

Imagine that we want to find out what variable derived from the elevation raster layer explains the best the air temperature variability. We could select between the mean, median, standard deviation and maximum of elevation. map() loops over a vector or a list that can be also considered a vector. The functions that are placed inside the map() function and whose arguments are changed needs to be vectorized.

# because map() loops over a vectors, first, create a vector of names of functions we want to apply
fns <- c("mean", "median", "sd", "max")

# pipe operator pairs well with map()
# by default, map() produces a list that can also be a column of a tibble
statistics <- tibble(fns = fns)

# often, anonymous functions are applied within map()
statistics <- statistics |> 
  mutate(stats = fns |> 
           map(\(x) bind_cols(kraje() |> 
                                st_drop_geometry() |> 
                                select(NAZ_CZNUTS3),
                              extract(czdem2,
                                      kraje(),
                                      fun = x,
                                      ID = F,
                                      na.rm = T)) |> 
                 as_tibble()))

statistics

library(furrr)

# this works on Windows
plan(multisession,
     workers = availableCores())

# since terra utilizes external functions written in C++, raster layers need to be wrapped first, and then unwrapped in another functions applied by the slaves
czdem2_wrapped <- wrap(czdem2)

# we also rather create a new sf object with administrative regions so that this vector layer is not downloaded several times
regions <- kraje()

tibble(fns = fns) |> 
  mutate(stats = fns |> 
           future_map(\(x) bind_cols(regions |> 
                                       st_drop_geometry() |> 
                                       select(NAZ_CZNUTS3),
                                     terra::extract(unwrap(czdem2_wrapped), # there are often coflicts regarding different extract() functions from different packages
                                                    regions,
                                                    fun = x,
                                                    ID = F,
                                                    na.rm = T)) |> 
                        as_tibble() |> 
                        left_join(zonalstats,
                                  join_by(NAZ_CZNUTS3)),
                      .options = furrr_options(seed = NULL, # we do not want to generate pseudorandom numbers
                                               packages = c("tidyverse", # slaves need to know the packages from which the applied functions come
                                                            "terra",
                                                            "RCzechia"), # sf is loaded automatically
                                               globals = c("zonalstats", # slaves need to know the variables from the Global Environment
                                                           "czdem2_wrapped",
                                                           "regions"))),
         models = stats |>
           future_map(\(x)
                      lm(units::drop_units(tavg) ~ CZE_elv_msk,
                         data = x) |> 
                        tidy(),
                      .options = furrr_options(seed = NULL,
                                               packages = c("tidyverse",
                                                            "broom")))) |> 
  select(fns, models) |> 
  unnest(models) |> 
  filter(term == "CZE_elv_msk") |> 
  slice_min(order_by = p.value,
            n = 1)

# we can see that it depends on the situation, and we need to have own experience
# perhaps, with rising amount of data, the parallel approach would win
# also, it highly depends on the machine we have at hand (RAM, number of logical cores, etc.)

map() has many variants according to what they return. However, what follows after the underscore in the names of those functions very well suggests what is returned. For instance, map_lgl() returns a logical vector. It must be ensured that the result of each loop satisfies the condition for applying such functions. There is also a difference between map() and walk(). As a rule of thumb, walk() is applied where something goes outside R. This includes saving files to a disc. More about functional programming can be found in a chapter of Wickham et al. (2023). More about programming in R in general can be found in other books as well Wickham and Bryan (2023).
